    "para" :
    true,
    
    "html" :
    
    
    "             For this process, first draw a boundary circle              <a class=\"qv qv-grafik\" href=\"\" target=\"PIWIS287bd9c0c9a31004821edab5c05fd45f2\">-B-</a>              at the centre of the dent using wax chalk. This circle is to prevent the tool from being pulled too far into the centre. This could cause the dent to break up into numerous tiny dents and make any further work more difficult.         "
    
    }
    
    }
    ,
    
    {
    
    
    "type" :
    
    
    "static"
    ,
    
    "inputs" : {
    
    
    "para" :
    true,
    
    "html" :
    
    
    "             Use the large ball tool with the large round plastic attachment. Place the tool at the edge of the dent              <a class=\"qv qv-grafik\" href=\"\" target=\"PIWIS287bd9c0c9a31004821edab5c05fd45f2\">-A-</a>              first at 12 o'clock and using gentle pressure approach the boundary circle with gradually increasing pressure. Continue working from 11 o'clock to 1 o'clock, from 10 o'clock to 2 o'clock, etc. from the outer edge of the dent right up to the boundary circle. The pressure must not be too great as this could cause ridges. Once the dent has been shrunk back to the boundary circle, continue using the point-by-point clock method              <a class=\"qv qv-grafik\" href=\"\" target=\"PIWIS287bd9c0c9a31004821edab5c05fd45f2\">-C-</a>             .         "
    
